# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: agave
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:agave/agave-americana] Despite being called "American aloe" in common parlance, *Agave americana* is not closely related to *Aloe* species.
[src:agave/agave-americana] The common name "century plant" stems from its monocarpic nature of flowering only once at the end of its long life.
[src:agave/agave-americana] After flowering, the plant dies but produces adventitious shoots from the base, allowing its growth to continue.
[src:agave/agave-americana] Although it is called the century plant, it typically lives only 10 to 30 years.
[src:agave/agave-americana] It has a spread around 1.8–3.0 m (6–10 ft) with gray-green leaves measuring 0.9–1.5 m (3–5 ft) in length, each with a prickly margin and a heavy spike at the tip that can pierce deeply.
[src:agave/agave-americana] Towards the end of its life, the plant produces a tall, branched stalk adorned with yellow blossoms, which can reach a height of 8–9 m (25–30 ft).
[src:agave/agave-americana] The species was given its binomial name *Agave americana* by Carl Linnaeus in the first edition of *Species Plantarum* (1753).
[src:agave/agave-americana] This name is the one still in use today.
[src:agave/agave-americana] When grown as a houseplant, *A. americana* is tolerant of light levels ranging from direct sunlight to shade, and requires minimal watering.
[src:agave/agave-americana] It undergoes a winter resting period at temperatures around 10 to 12 °C (50 to 54 °F).
[src:agave/agave-americana] It thrives in a highly porous, sandy potting soil, should be allowed to dry out between waterings, and should be repotted annually in the spring.
[src:agave/agave-americana] The World Checklist of Selected Plant Families recognizes two subspecies and two varieties of *A. americana*.
[src:agave/agave-americana] Additionally, there are several cultivars, including 'Marginata,' 'Mediopicta,' 'Mediopicta Alba,' 'Mediopicta Aurea,' 'Striata,' and 'Variegata.' Some of these cultivars, along with the parent species, have received the Royal Horticultural Society's Award of Garden Merit.
[src:agave/agave-americana] (those marked agm, as well as the parent species, have gained the Royal Horticultural Society's Award of Garden Merit).
[src:agave/agave-americana] In the tequila-producing regions of Mexico, agaves are known as *mezcales*.
[src:agave/agave-americana] Mezcal refers to the high-alcohol product obtained through fermented agave distillation, and *A. americana* is among the several *Agave* species used for this purpose.
[src:agave/agave-americana] The specific mezcal known as tequila is produced from *Agave tequilana*, commonly referred to as "blue agave." Mezcal comes in various types, some of which may be flavored with the intensely pungent mezcal worm.
[src:agave/agave-americana] Mezcal and tequila, despite being produced from agave plants, differ from pulque in their sugar extraction techniques and classification as distilled spirits.
[src:agave/agave-americana] In mezcal and tequila production, the sugars are obtained by heating the piñas (or hearts) of the plants in ovens, as opposed to collecting aguamiel from the cut stalk of the plant.
[src:agave/agave-americana] Therefore, if pulque were to be distilled, it would not be classified as mezcal but rather as a distinct beverage.
[src:agave/agave-americana] Agaves are also found throughout Latin America and are used in similar ways.
[src:agave/agave-americana] In Ecuador, the equivalent of *pulque* is known as *guarango*, which has recently been distilled as *miske*.
[src:agave/agave-americana] Agave nectar is marketed as a natural sweetener with a low glycemic index, primarily due to its high fructose content.
[src:agave/agave-americana] The leaves of *A. americana* yield fibers called *pita*, which are suitable for making ropes, nets, bags, sacks, matting, and coarse cloth.
[src:agave/agave-americana] They are also used for leather embroidery in a technique known as *piteado*.
[src:agave/agave-americana] Both pulque and maguey fiber played significant roles in the pre-Columbian economy of Mexico.
[src:agave/agave-americana] The plant holds heraldic significance and is featured in the coat of arms of Don Diego de Mendoza, a Native American governor of the village of Ajacuba, Hidalgo.
[src:agave/agave-americana] Additionally, the Aztecs used the pulped leaves of *A. americana* to create paper.
[src:agave/agave-americana] The fragments known as the Humboldt fragments were made using this technique.
[src:agave/agave-attenuata] In addition to its inflorescence, when compared with other *Agave* species, *A. attenuata* is further unique with its soft, spineless leaves and the fact that it does not rapidly asexually produce dozens of "runners" or "pups" from the rhizome of the mother plant.
[src:agave/agave-attenuata] These factors have helped *A. attenuata* earn a positive reputation amongst gardeners as easy-to-manage; the species has become extremely popular as an ornamental plant in appropriate climates and zones, especially the American Southwest, Latin America and the Mediterranean.
[src:agave/agave-attenuata] Several unique forms and cultivars have been created and made available on the plant market, such as the white-variegated *A. attenuata* 'Variegata' and 'Ray of Light', or the teal-hued 'Boutin Blue'.
[src:agave/agave-attenuata] The similarly teal-leaved 'Blue Flame' was achieved with the cross of *Agave attenuata* x *Agave shawii*.
[src:agave/agave-attenuata] Although particularly young or smaller plants can appear acaulescent, stems often mature to between 50 and 150 cm (20 and 59 in) in length, with older, desiccated leaves falling off and leaving the woody stems visible.
[src:agave/agave-attenuata] The leaves are ovate-acuminate, 50–70 cm (20–28 in) long and 12–16 cm (5–6 in) wide, pale in color, ranging from a light gray to a light yellowish-green.
[src:agave/agave-attenuata] There are neither teeth, nor terminal spines, although the leaves taper to soft points that fray with age.
[src:agave/agave-attenuata] The numerous, broad, succulent, tapering leaves are slightly less rigid than the leaves of most *Agave* species; they are a bright glaucous gray to light yellowish-green and stingless.
[src:agave/agave-attenuata] The inflorescence is a dense raceme 2.5 to 3 meters (8.2 to 9.8 ft) high (usually curved), with greenish-yellow flowers, developing after many years.
[src:agave/agave-attenuata] As with other *Agave* species, the species is monocarpic, meaning that, rather than sending flowers out from the side of its stem and continuing living (like the succulent genera *Crassula* or *Sedum*, for example), the entire rosette morphs into the giant inflorescence.
[src:agave/agave-attenuata] After many months, this blossom subsequently dies following pollination and seed development, although numerous plantlets consequently sprout, both from the base of the plant and from the flower raceme.
[src:agave/agave-attenuata] In nature, when the inflorescence finally dries and falls to the ground, the young plants growing from it will inevitably root into the ground, thus forming a brand-new colony.
[src:agave/agave-attenuata] The Latin specific epithet *attenuata* means "with a narrow point".
[src:agave/agave-attenuata] Specimens were sent to Kew Gardens by the explorer Galeotti in 1834 from an unspecified location in central Mexico.
[src:agave/agave-attenuata] A more recent study has reported it from Jalisco, on the west coast and east of Mexico State, in small colonies at elevations between 1,900 to 2,500 meters (6,200 to 8,200 ft), but there have been few sightings, suggesting this species is rare in the wild.
[src:agave/agave-attenuata] It is reportedly naturalized in Libya and Madeira and is widely spread through the Mediterranean and the rest of Macaronesia.
[src:agave/agave-attenuata] In cultivation, *Agave attenuata* is said to prefer relatively moist loamy soil, although it can cope with poor soil and dry conditions.
[src:agave/agave-attenuata] It should be protected from direct sunlight in summer and from long periods of frost.
[src:agave/agave-mythology] In Greek mythology, **Agave** (/əˈɡeɪviː/; Ancient Greek: Ἀγαύη, romanized: *Agaúē*, lit.
[src:agave/agave] Many plants in this genus may be considered perennial, because they require several to many years to mature and flower.
[src:agave/agave] However, most *Agave* species are more accurately described as monocarpic rosettes or multiannuals, since each individual rosette flowers only once and then dies; a small number of *Agave* species are polycarpic.
[src:agave/agave] Along with plants from the closely related genera *Yucca*, *Hesperoyucca*, and *Hesperaloe,* various *Agave* species are popular ornamental plants in hot, dry climates, as they require very little supplemental water to survive.
[src:agave/agave] Some *Agave* species are known by the common name "century plant".
[src:agave/agave] In other regions, it goes by different names.
[src:agave/agave] In the Chinese, Japanese, and Korean languages, it is referred to as the compound word *dragon tongue orchid* (simplified Chinese: 龙舌兰; traditional Chinese: 龍舌蘭; pinyin: *lóngshélán*; Japanese: 竜舌蘭, romanized: *ryūzetsuran*; Korean: 용설란; Hanja: 龍舌蘭; RR: *yongseollan*).
[src:agave/agave] In Malta, it is referred to as *Sabbara*; In Maltese, Agave americana is referred to as "Sabbara tal-Amerika", and Agave sisalana is referred to as "Sabbara ta' Sisal".
[src:agave/agave] The succulent leaves of most *Agave* species have sharp marginal teeth, an extremely sharp terminal spine, and are very fibrous inside.
[src:agave/agave] The stout stem is usually extremely short, which may make the plant appear as though it is stemless.
[src:agave/agave] Agaves can be confused with cacti, aloes, or stonecrops, but although these plants all share similar morphological adaptations to arid environments (e.g. succulence), each group belongs to a different plant family and probably experienced convergent evolution.
[src:agave/agave] Further, cactus (Cactaceae) and stonecrop (Crassulaceae) lineages are eudicots, while aloes (Asphodelaceae) and agaves (Asparagaceae) are monocots.
[src:agave/agave] The agave root system, consisting of a network of shallow rhizomes, allows the agave to efficiently capture moisture from rain, condensation, and dew.
[src:agave/agave] In addition to growing from seeds, most agaves produce 'pups' – young plants from runners.
[src:agave/agave] *Agave vilmoriniana* (the octopus agave) produces hundreds of pups on its bloom stalk.
[src:agave/agave] Agave leaves store the plant's water and are crucial to its continued existence.
[src:agave/agave] The coated leaf surface prevents evaporation.
[src:agave/agave] The leaves also have sharp, spiked edges.
[src:agave/agave] The spikes discourage predators from eating the plant or using it as a source of water and are so tough that ancient peoples used them for sewing needles.
[src:agave/agave] Some agaves bloom at a height up to 9 m (30 ft) so that they are far out of reach to animals that might attack them.
[src:agave/agave] Smaller species, such as *Agave lechuguilla*, have smaller bloom stalks.
[src:agave/agave] The genus name *Agave* come from the Ancient Greek αγαυή *agauê* from ἀγαυός *agauós* meaning "illustrious, noble" having to do with very tall flower spikes found on its many species.
[src:agave/agave] The genus *Agave* was erected by Carl Linnaeus in 1753, initially with four species.
[src:agave/agave] The first listed was *Agave americana*, now the type species.
[src:agave/agave] In the Cronquist system and others, *Agave* was placed in the family Liliaceae, but phylogenetic analyses of DNA sequences later showed it did not belong there.
[src:agave/agave] In the APG II system, *Agave* was placed in the segregated family Agavaceae.
[src:agave/agave] When this system was superseded by the APG III system in 2009, the Agavaceae were subsumed into the expanded family Asparagaceae, and *Agave* was treated as one of 18 genera in the subfamily Agavoideae, a position retained in the APG IV system of 2016.
[src:agave/agave] However, Agavaceae had regained its taxonomic status as an independent family by 2020.
[src:agave/agave] Agaves and close relatives have long presented significant taxonomic difficulty.
[src:agave/agave] These difficulties could be due to the relatively young evolutionary age of the group (major diversification events of the group most likely occurred 8–10 million years ago), ease of hybridization between species (and even genera), incomplete lineage sorting, and long generation times.
[src:agave/agave] Within a species, morphological variations can be considerable, especially in cultivation; many named species may be variants of original wild-type species that horticulturalists bred to appear unique in cultivation.
[src:agave/agave] With the advent of DNA sequencing, new karyologic and evolutionary phylogenetic studies showed that the genera *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes* were genetically nested within the traditional circumscription of *Agave*, rendering the genus paraphyletic.
[src:agave/agave] Early in the 21st century, these new phylogenetic results led to a reclassification of to include *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes* together as *Agave* subgenus *Manfreda*.
[src:agave/agave] There was reaction against the changes from those who noted that the large morphological differences between the genera in this new *Agave* s.l. making them "counter-intuitive from a horticultural point of view".
[src:agave/agave] *Manfreda* morphologically differs from the classic *Agave* description in being herbaceous and bulbous, while *Polianthes* are deciduous with narrow leaves and no spines.
[src:agave/agave] Mexican taxonomists have continued to adhere to the traditional classifications and have published new species of *Polianthes*.
[src:agave/agave] Thus, based on a wider consideration of previously established genetic, morphological, and estimated genetic divergence times, Vázquez-García et al. proposed a narrower circumscription of *Agave* by creating three new genera: *Echinoagave*, *Paleoagave* and *Paraagave*.
[src:agave/agave] These new genera have gained some acceptance, and pave the way for a reconsideration of *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes*.
[src:agave/agave] Some commonly grown species include *Agave americana*, *A. angustifolia*, *A. attenuata*, *A. murpheyi*, *A. palmeri*, *A. parryi*, *A. parviflora*, *A. tequilana*, *A. victoriae-reginae*, and *A. vilmoriniana*.
[src:agave/agave] One of the most familiar species is *A. americana*, a native of tropical America.
[src:agave/agave] Common names include century plant, *maguey* (in Mexico), or American aloe (though not related to the genus *Aloe*).
[src:agave/agave] The name "century plant" refers to the long time the plant takes to flower.
[src:agave/agave] The number of years before flowering occurs depends on the vigor of the individual plant, the richness of the soil, and the climate; during these years, the plant is storing in its fleshy leaves the nourishment required for the effort of flowering.
[src:agave/agave] Some species contain components in their juice which can cause dermatitis for some people.
[src:agave/agave] The ethnobotany of the agave was described by William H.
[src:agave/agave] The four major edible parts of the agave are the flowers, the leaves, the stalks or basal rosettes, and the sap (in Spanish: *aguamiel*, meaning "honey water").
[src:agave/agave] The sap of some species can also be used as soap.
[src:agave/agave] Each agave plant produces several pounds of edible flowers during its final season.
[src:agave/agave] The stalks, which are ready during the summer, before the blossom, weigh several pounds each.
[src:agave/agave] Roasted, they are sweet and can be chewed to extract the sap or *aguamiel*, like sugarcane.
[src:agave/agave] When dried out, the stalks can be used to make didgeridoos.
[src:agave/agave] The leaves may be collected in winter and spring, when the plants are rich in sap, for eating.
[src:agave/agave] The leaves of several species also yield fiber, for instance, *A. sisalana*, the sisal hemp, and *A. decipiens*, the false sisal hemp.
[src:agave/agave] *A. americana* is the source of pita fiber, and is used as a fiber plant in Mexico, the West Indies, and southern Europe.
[src:agave/agave] The agave, especially *A. murpheyi*, was a major food source for the prehistoric indigenous people of the Southwestern United States.
[src:agave/agave] The Hohokam of southern Arizona cultivated large areas of agave.
[src:agave/agave] The Navajo similarly found many uses for the agave plant.
[src:agave/agave] A beverage is squeezed from the baked fibers, and the heads can be baked or boiled, pounded into flat sheets, sun dried, and stored for future use.
[src:agave/agave] The baked, dried heads are also boiled and made into an edible paste, eaten whole, or made into soup.
[src:agave/agave] The leaves are eaten boiled, and the young, tender flowering stalks and shoots are roasted and eaten as well.
[src:agave/agave] The fibers are used to make rope, the leaves are used to line baking pits, and the sharp-pointed leaf tips are used to make basketry awls.
[src:agave/agave] During the development of the inflorescence, sap rushes to the base of the young flower stalk.
[src:agave/agave] Agave syrup (commonly called agave nectar), a sweetener derived from the sap, is used as an alternative to sugar in cooking, and can be added to breakfast cereals as a binding agent.
[src:agave/agave] Extracts from agave leaves are under preliminary research for their potential use as food additives.
[src:agave/agave] The sap of *A. americana* and other species is used in Mexico and Mesoamerica to produce pulque, an alcoholic beverage.
[src:agave/agave] The flower shoot is cut out and the sap collected and subsequently fermented.
[src:agave/agave] By distillation, a spirit called mezcal is prepared; one of the best-known forms of mezcal is tequila.
[src:agave/agave] *azul* is used in the production of tequila.
[src:agave/agave] *A. angustifolia* is widely used in the production of mezcal and pulque, though at least 10 other *Agave* species are also known to be used for this.
[src:agave/agave] Agave can be used as the raw material for industrial production of fructans as a prebiotic dietary fiber.
[src:agave/agave] Agave contains fructooligosaccharides, which are naturally occurring oligosaccharides that support safely subjecting peanut-allergic people to allergen immunotherapy.
[src:agave/agave] Resulting from its natural habitat in stressful environments, agave is under preliminary research for its potential use in germplasm conservation and in biotechnology to better anticipate the economic effects of global climate change.
[src:agave/agave] It may also have use as a bioethanol or bioenergy feedstock.
[src:agave/agave] Agave plantations have potential applications on marginal lands unsuitable for grain crops.
[src:agave/apg-ii-system] The **APG II system** (**Angiosperm Phylogeny Group II system**) of plant classification is the second, now obsolete, version of a modern, mostly molecular-based, system of plant taxonomy that was published in April 2003 by the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group.
[src:agave/apg-ii-system] It was a revision of the first APG system, published in 1998, and was superseded in 2009 by a further revision, the APG III system.
[src:agave/apg-ii-system] Each of the APG systems represents the broad consensus of a number of systematic botanists, united in the APG, working at several institutions worldwide.
[src:agave/apg-ii-system] The APG II system recognized 45 orders, five more than the APG system.
[src:agave/apg-ii-system] The new orders were Austrobaileyales, Canellales, Gunnerales, Celastrales, and Crossosomatales, all of which were families unplaced as to order, although contained in supra-ordinal clades, in the APG system.
[src:agave/apg-ii-system] APG II recognized 457 families, five fewer than the APG system.
[src:agave/apg-ii-system] Thirty-nine of the APG II families were not placed in any order, but 36 of the 39 were placed in a supra-ordinal clade within the angiosperms.
[src:agave/apg-ii-system] Fifty-five of the families came to be known as "bracketed families".
[src:agave/apg-ii-system] They were optional segregates of families that could be circumscribed in a larger sense.
[src:agave/apg-ii-system] The APG II system was influential and was adopted in whole or in part (sometimes with modifications) in a number of references.
[src:agave/apg-ii-system] It was superseded 6½ years later by the APG III system, published in October 2009.
[src:agave/apg-ii-system] Shown below is the classification in full detail, except for the fifteen genera and three families that were unplaced in APG II.
[src:agave/apg-ii-system] The unplaced taxa were listed at the end of the appendix in a section entitled "Taxa of Uncertain Position".
[src:agave/apg-ii-system] Under some of the clades are listed the families that were placed incertae sedis in that clade.
[src:agave/apg-ii-system] This means that their relationship to other members of the clade is not known.
[src:agave/apg-ii-system] Note: "+ ..." = optionally separate family, that may be split off from the preceding family.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] The **APG III system** of flowering plant classification is the third version of a modern, mostly molecular-based, system of plant taxonomy being developed by the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group (APG).
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] Published in 2009, it was superseded in 2016 by a further revision, the APG IV system.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] The APG III system recognized all of the 45 orders of the previous system, as well as 14 new ones.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] The order Ceratophyllales was erroneously marked as a new order, as it had been recognized in both of the previous APG systems.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] The designation of alternative "bracketed families" was abandoned in APG III, because its inclusion in the previous system had been unpopular.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] APG III recognized 413 families, 43 fewer than in the previous system.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] Forty-four of the 55 "bracketed families" were discontinued, and 20 other families were discontinued as well.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] 21 families were accepted in the APG III system which had not been in the previous system, and a few families were moved to a different position.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] The number of families not placed in any order was reduced from 39 to 10.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] Apodanthaceae and Cynomoriaceae were placed among the angiosperms, incertae sedis, that is, not in any group within the angiosperms.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] Eight other families were placed incertae sedis in various supra-ordinal groups within the angiosperms.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] The paragraph below shows the number of families in each order and the placement of those families that were not included in any order.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] These figures were produced by simply counting the families in the text of the paper that established APG III.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] SUPRA-ORDINAL GROUPS: commelinids (1), basal eudicots (1), Pentapetalae (1), lamiids incertae sedis (3), core lamiids (2), angiosperms incertae sedis (2).
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] The circumscription of the family Icacinaceae remains especially doubtful.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] *Apodytes* and its close relative, Rhaphiostylis, as well as *Emmotum*, *Cassinopsis*, and a few other genera were provisionally retained within it until further studies can determine whether they properly belong there.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] Three genera (*Gumillea*, *Nicobariodendron*, and *Petenaea*) were placed within the angiosperms incertae sedis.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] *Nicobariodendron* and *Petenaea* were newly added to the list.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] The classification is shown below in two versions.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] The short version goes to the level of orders and of families unplaced in an order.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] The detailed version shows all the families.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] Orders at the same level in the classification are arranged alphabetically.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] Note that orders may not contain the same families as in earlier versions of the APG system (APG system, APG II system).
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] Further detail on relationships can be seen in the phylogenetic tree below.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] The APG III system was based on a phylogenetic tree for the angiosperms which included all of the 59 orders and 4 of the unplaced families.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] The systematic positions of the other 6 unplaced families was so uncertain that they could not be placed in any of the polytomies in the tree.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] They are shown in the classification table entitled "Detailed version" above, 4 in Euasterids I and 2 in Taxa of uncertain position.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] The phylogenetic tree shown below was published with the APG III system, but without some of the labels that are added here.
[src:agave/apg-iii-system] A number of subfamilies have been proposed to replace some of the families which were optional (i.e. bracketed) in APG II, but have been discontinued in APG III.
[src:agave/apg-iv-system] The **APG IV system** of flowering plant classification is the fourth version of a modern, mostly molecular-based, system of plant taxonomy for flowering plants (angiosperms) being developed by the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group (APG).
[src:agave/apg-iv-system] It was published in 2016, seven years after its predecessor the APG III system was published in 2009, and 18 years after the first APG system was published in 1998.
[src:agave/apg-iv-system] In 2009, a linear arrangement of the system was published separately; the APG IV paper includes such an arrangement, cross-referenced to the 2009 one.
[src:agave/apg-iv-system] Compared to the APG III system, the APG IV system recognizes five new orders (Boraginales, Dilleniales, Icacinales, Metteniusales and Vahliales), along with some new families, making a total of 64 angiosperm orders and 416 families.
[src:agave/apg-iv-system] In general, the authors describe their philosophy as "conservative", based on making changes from APG III only where "a well-supported need" has been demonstrated.
[src:agave/apg-iv-system] This has sometimes resulted in placements that are not compatible with published studies, but where further research is needed before the classification can be changed.
[src:agave/apg-iv-system] Like the earlier APG systems, the APG IV revision is based on a phylogenetic tree for the angiosperms, as shown below.
